\par \plain\pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\*\bkmkstart Help}{\*\bkmkend Help}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Lynx online help
\par \plain \f1\fs18 Online help is available while viewing any document. Press the '\plain \f1\i\fs18 ?\plain \f1\fs18 ' or '\plain \f1\i\fs18 H\plain \f1\fs18 ' key (or the '\plain \f1\i\fs18 h\plain \f1\fs18 ' key if vi-like key movement is not on) to see a list of help topics. See the section titled\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 Navigating hypertext documents with Lynx\plain \f1\fs18 \~for information on navigating through the help files.
\par In addition, a summary description of all the Lynx keystroke commands and their key bindings is available by pressing the '\plain \f1\i\fs18 K\plain \f1\fs18 ' key (or the '\plain \f1\i\fs18 k\plain \f1\fs18 ' key if vi-like key movement is not on). [\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]
\par If you want to recall recent status-line messages, you can do so by entering the `g' command, followed by `LYNXMESSAGES:'.
\par {\*\bkmkstart Local}{\*\bkmkend Local}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Viewing local files with Lynx
\par \plain \f1\fs18 Lynx can be started by entering the Lynx command along with the name of a file to display. For example these commands could all be used to display an arbitrary ASCII text or HTML file:UNIXlynx filenamelynx /home/my-dir/filenamelynx ~/filenameVMSlynx filenamelynx dua5:[my-directory]filenamelynx /dua5/my-directory/filenamelynx ~/filenamelynx sys$login:filenamelynx /sys$login/filenameWin32/DOSlynx file:///filenamelynx filenamelynx c:/dir/filenamelynx //n/dir/filename
\par When executed, Lynx will clear the screen and display as much of the specified file as will fit on the screen. Pressing a\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 down-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~will bring up the next screen, and pressing an\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 up-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~will bring up the previous screen. If no file is specified at startup, a default file will be displayed, depending on settings e.g., in\plain \f1\i\fs18 lynx.cfg\plain \f1\fs18 .
\par Lynx will display local files written in the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 HyperText Markup Language\plain \f1\fs18 \~(\plain \f1\i\fs18 HTML\plain \f1\fs18 ), if the file's name ends with the characters\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 .html\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 .htm\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 .shtml\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 .htmlx\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 .html3\plain \f1\fs18 , or\plain \f1\i\fs18 .ht3\plain \f1\fs18 . HTML is a file format that allows users to create a file that contains (among other things) hypertext links to other files. Several files linked together may be described as a\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 hypertext document\plain \f1\fs18 . If the filename does not have one of the suffixes mapped by Lynx to HTML, the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 -force_html\plain \f1\fs18 \~command line option can be included to force treatment of the file as hypertext.
\par When Lynx displays an HTML file, it shows links as "bold face" text, except for one link, which is shown as "highlighted" text. Whether "boldface" or "highlighted" text shows up as reverse video, boldface type, or a color change, etc. depends on the display device being used (and the way in which that device has been configured). Lynx has no control over the exact presentation of links.
\par The one link displayed as "highlighted" text is the currently "selected" link. Lynx will display the file associated with the selected link when a\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 right-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~or a\plain \f1\i\fs18 Return\plain \f1\fs18 \~key is pressed. To select a particular link, press the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 up-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 down-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~keys until the desired link becomes "highlighted," and then press the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 right-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Return\plain \f1\fs18 \~key to view the linked information. Information included in the HTML file tells Lynx where to find the linked file and what kind of server will provide it (i.e., HTTP, Gopher, etc.).
\par Lynx renders HTML files and saves the rendition (and the source, if so configured in the\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 lynx.cfg\plain \f1\fs18 \~file) for initial display and should you select the link again. If you do select a link again and have reason to desire a new fetch and rendering of the file, use the NOCACHE command, normally mapped to '\plain \f1\i\fs18 x\plain \f1\fs18 ' and '\plain \f1\i\fs18 X\plain \f1\fs18 ', instead of the\plain \f1\i\fs18 right-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Return\plain \f1\fs18 \~key when positioned on the link. You also can force a new fetch and rendering of the currently displayed document via the RELOAD command, normally mapped to\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Control-R\plain \f1\fs18 .
\par When a binary file is encountered Lynx will ask the user if he/she wishes to download the file or cancel. If the user selects '\plain \f1\i\fs18 D'\plain \f1\fs18 \~for download, Lynx will transfer the file into a temporary location and present the user with a list of options. The only default option is\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Save to disk\plain \f1\fs18 , which is disabled if Lynx is running in anonymous mode. Additional download methods may be defined in the\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 lynx.cfg\plain \f1\fs18 \~file. Programs like kermit, zmodem and FTP are some possible options. [\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]
\par {\*\bkmkstart Leaving}{\*\bkmkend Leaving}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Leaving Lynx
\par \plain \f1\fs18 To exit Lynx use the '\plain \f1\i\fs18 q\plain \f1\fs18 ' command. You will be asked whether you really want to quit. Answering '\plain \f1\i\fs18 y\plain \f1\fs18 ' will exit and '\plain \f1\i\fs18 n\plain \f1\fs18 ' will return you to the current document. Use '\plain \f1\i\fs18 Q\plain \f1\fs18 ' or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Control-D\plain \f1\fs18 \~to quit without verification. [\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]
\par {\*\bkmkstart Remote}{\*\bkmkend Remote}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Starting Lynx with a Remote File
\par \plain \f1\fs18 If you wish to view a remote file (that is, a file residing on some computer system other than the one upon which you are running Lynx) without first viewing a local file, you must identify that file by using a Uniform Resource Locator (URL). URLs take the general form:
\par PROTOCOL :// HOST / PATH
\par where
\par PROTOCOLidentifies the communications protocol (\plain \f1\i\fs18 scheme\plain \f1\fs18 ) used by the server that will provide the file. As mentioned earlier, Lynx (and any WWW client) can interact with a variety of servers, each with its own protocol.HOSTis the Internet address of the computer system on which the server is running, andPATHis a scheme-specific field which for some schemes may correspond to a directory path and/or filename.Here are some sample URLs.HTTP (HyperText Transfer Protocol)http://www.subir.com/lynx.htmlGophergopher://gopher.micro.umn.edu/11/FTP (File Transfer Protocol)ftp://ftp2.cc.ukans.edu/pub/lynx/READMEWAIS (Wide Area Information Service protocol)wais://cnidr.org/directory-of-serversA URL may be specified to Lynx on the command line, as in:lynx http://kufacts.cc.ukans.edu/cwis/kufacts_start.htmlLynx also will attempt to create a complete URL if you include adequate portions of it in the startfile argument. For example:
\par 1234.6789.1234.6789.1234.6789.1234.6789.1234.6789.1234.6789.1234.6789.1234.6789\'0a 
\par \plain \f1\i\fs18                  wfbr\plain \f1\fs18           will be expanded to:\'0a 
\par \plain \f1\i\fs18       http://www.wfbr.edu/\plain \f1\fs18      and:\'0a 
\par \plain \f1\i\fs18              ftp.more.net/pub\plain \f1\fs18   will be expanded to:\'0a 
\par \plain \f1\i\fs18        ftp://ftp.more.net/pub
\par \plain \f1\fs18 See\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 URL Schemes Supported by Lynx\plain \f1\fs18 \~for more detailed information. [\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]
\par {\*\bkmkstart EnVar}{\*\bkmkend EnVar}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Starting Lynx with the WWW_HOME environment variable.
\par \plain \f1\fs18 You may also specify a starting file for Lynx using the WWW_HOME environment variable,UNIXkshexport WWW_HOME=http://www.w3.org/cshsetenv WWW_HOME http://www.w3.org/VMSdefine "WWW_HOME" "http://www.w3.org/"win32WWW_HOME=http://www.w3.org/ [or in registry]Note that on VMS the double-quoting\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 must\plain \f1\fs18 \~be included to preserve casing. [\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]
\par {\*\bkmkstart IntraDocNav}{\*\bkmkend IntraDocNav}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Navigating hypertext documents with Lynx
\par \plain \f1\fs18 The process of moving within a hypertext web, selecting and displaying links is known as "navigation." With Lynx almost all navigation can be accomplished with the arrow keys and the numeric keypad.                                       +-------+-------+-------+\'0a 
