\par There are also a few other keyboard commands to aid in navigation. The Control and Function keys used for navigation within the current document are described in\plain \f1\i\ul\fs18\cf1 Scrolling and Other useful commands\plain \f1\fs18 . Some additional commands depend on the fact that Lynx keeps a list of each link you visited to reach the current document, called the\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 History Page\plain \f1\fs18 , and a list of all links visited during the current Lynx session, called the\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 Visited Links Page\plain \f1\fs18 . The HISTORY keystroke command, normally mapped to\plain \f1\i\fs18 Backspace\plain \f1\fs18 \~or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Delete\plain \f1\fs18 , will show you the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 History Page\plain \f1\fs18 \~of links leading to your access of the current document. Any of the previous documents shown in the list may be revisited by selecting them from the history screen. The VLINKS keystroke command, normally mapped to uppercase '\plain \f1\i\fs18 V\plain \f1\fs18 ', will show the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Visited Links Page\plain \f1\fs18 , and you similarly can select links in that list. The MAIN_MENU keystroke command, normally mapped to '\plain \f1\i\fs18 m\plain \f1\fs18 ' and '\plain \f1\i\fs18 M\plain \f1\fs18 ', will take you back to the starting document unless you specified the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 -homepage=URL\plain \f1\fs18 \~option at the command line. Also, the LIST and ADDRLIST keystroke commands, normally mapped to '\plain \f1\i\fs18 l\plain \f1\fs18 ' and\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 A\plain \f1\fs18 ' respectively, will create a compact lists of all the links in the current document, and they can be selected via those lists.
\par The '\plain \f1\i\fs18 i\plain \f1\fs18 ' key presents an index of documents. The default index offered contains many useful links, but can be changed in\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 lynx.cfg\plain \f1\fs18 \~or on the command line using the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 -index=URL\plain \f1\fs18 \~switch.
\par If you choose a link to a server with active access authorization, Lynx will automatically prompt for a username and a password. If you give the correct information, you will then be served the requested information. Lynx will automatically send your username and password to the same server if it is needed again. [\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]
\par {\*\bkmkstart Disposing}{\*\bkmkend Disposing}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Printing, Mailing, and Saving rendered files to disk.
\par \plain \f1\fs18 Rendered HTML documents, and plain text files, may be printed using the '\plain \f1\i\fs18 p\plain \f1\fs18 ' command while viewing the document. After pressing the '\plain \f1\i\fs18 p\plain \f1\fs18 ' key a menu of\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Print Options\plain \f1\fs18 will be displayed. The menu will vary according to several factors. First, some sites set up special accounts to let users run Lynx to access local information systems. Typically these accounts require no passwords and do not require users to identify themselves. As a result such accounts are called "anonymous" accounts, and their users are considered "anonymous" users. In most configurations, all Lynx users (including anonymous users) are able to mail files to themselves and print the entire file to the screen.
\par Additional print options are available for users who are using Lynx from their own accounts (that is, so-called "non-anonymous users"). In particular, the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Save to a local file\plain \f1\fs18 \~option allows you to save the document into a file on your disk space. Additional print options may also be available as configured in the\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 lynx.cfg\plain \f1\fs18 \~file.
\par Some options, such as\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Save to a local file\plain \f1\fs18 , involve prompting for an output filename. All output filename entries are saved in a circular buffer, and any previous entries can be retrieved for re-use by pressing the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 up-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 down-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~keys at the prompt.
\par Note that if you want exact copies of text files without any expansions of TAB characters to spaces you should use the\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 Download\plain \f1\fs18 \~options. [\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]
\par {\*\bkmkstart LocalSource}{\*\bkmkend LocalSource}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Viewing the HTML document source and editing documents
\par \plain \f1\fs18 When viewing HTML documents it is possible to retrieve and display the unrendered (i.e., the original HTML) source of the document by pressing the '\plain \f1\i\fs18 \\\plain \f1\fs18 ' (backslash) key. Lynx usually caches only the rendering of the document and doesn't keep the source (unless it is configured to do so in the\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 lynx.cfg\plain \f1\fs18 \~file), so to display the source unrendered, Lynx must reload it from the server or disk. When viewing unrendered documents you may print them as any normal document.
\par Selecting the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Print to a local file\plain \f1\fs18 \~option from the Print Menu, makes it possible to save the source of the document to disk so that you may have a local copy of the document source, but it is better to\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 Download\plain \f1\fs18 \~the source.
\par NOTE: When saving an HTML document it is important to name the document with a\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 .html\plain \f1\fs18 \~or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 .htm\plain \f1\fs18 \~extension, if you want to read it with Lynx again later.
\par Lynx can allow users to edit documents that reside on the local system. To enable editing, documents must be referenced using a "file:" URL or by specifying a plain filename on the command line as in the following two examples:
\par Commandlynx file://localhost/FULL/PATH/FILENAMElynx path/filename.htmlIn addition, the user must also specify an editor in the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Options Menu\plain \f1\fs18 \~so that Lynx knows which editor to use. If the file is specified correctly and an editor is defined, then you may edit documents by using the '\plain \f1\i\fs18 e\plain \f1\fs18 ' command. When the '\plain \f1\i\fs18 e\plain \f1\fs18 ' command is entered your specified editor is spawned to edit the file. After changes are completed, exit your editor and you will return to Lynx. Lynx will reload and render the file so that changes can be immediately examined. [\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]
\par {\*\bkmkstart RemoteSource}{\*\bkmkend RemoteSource}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Downloading and Saving source files.
\par \plain \f1\fs18 If the DOWNLOAD keystroke command ('\plain \f1\i\fs18 d\plain \f1\fs18 ' or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 D\plain \f1\fs18 ) is used when positioned on a link for an HTML, plain text, or binary file, Lynx will transfer the file, without rendering, into a temporary location and present the user with a list of options, just as it does when a link for a binary file of a type for which no viewer has been mapped is activated.
\par There is a default\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Download option\plain \f1\fs18 \~of\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Save to disk\plain \f1\fs18 . This is disabled if Lynx is running in anonymous mode. Any number of download methods such as kermit and zmodem may be defined in addition to this default in the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 lynx.cfg\plain \f1\fs18 \~file. Using the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Save to disk\plain \f1\fs18 \~option under the PRINT command after viewing the source of an HTML with the VIEW SOURCE (\plain \f1\i\fs18 \\\plain \f1\fs18 ) command will result in a file which differs from the original source in various ways such as tab characters expanded to spaces. Lynx formats the source presentation in this mode. On the other hand, if the DOWNLOAD command is used, the only change will be that Lynx optionally puts
