\par Some options, such as\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Save to disk\plain \f1\fs18 , involve prompting for an output filename. All output filename entries are saved in a circular buffer, and any previous entries can be retrieved for re-use by pressing the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 up-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 down-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~keys at the prompt. [\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]
\par {\*\bkmkstart ReDo}{\*\bkmkend ReDo}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Reloading files and refreshing the display
\par \plain \f1\fs18 The RELOAD (\plain \f1\i\fs18 Control-R\plain \f1\fs18 ) command will reload and re-render the file that you are currently viewing. The REFRESH (\plain \f1\i\fs18 Control-L\plain \f1\fs18 \~or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Control-W\plain \f1\fs18 ) command will refresh or wipe the screen to remove or correct any errors that may be caused by operating system or other messages.
\par The NOCACHE ('\plain \f1\i\fs18 x\plain \f1\fs18 ' or '\plain \f1\i\fs18 X\plain \f1\fs18 ') command can be used in lieu of ACTIVATE (\plain \f1\i\fs18 Return\plain \f1\fs18 \~or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 right-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 ) to request an uncached copy and new rendition for the current link, or resubmission of a FORM, if a cache from a previous request or submission exits. The request or submission will include\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Pragma: no-cache\plain \f1\fs18 \~and\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Cache-Control: no-cache\plain \f1\fs18 \~in its headers. Note that FORMs with POST content will be resubmitted regardless of whether the NOCACHE or ACTIVATE command is used (see\~\plain \f1\i\ul\fs18\cf1 Lynx and HTML Forms\plain \f1\fs18 ). [\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]
\par {\*\bkmkstart Search}{\*\bkmkend Search}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Lynx searching commands
\par \plain \f1\fs18 Two commands activate searching in Lynx: '\plain \f1\i\fs18 /\plain \f1\fs18 ' and '\plain \f1\i\fs18 s\plain \f1\fs18 '.
\par While viewing a normal document use the '\plain \f1\i\fs18 /\plain \f1\fs18 ' command to find a word or phrase within the current document. The search type will depend on the search option setting in the\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 Options Menu\plain \f1\fs18 . The search options are case sensitive and case insensitive. These searches are entirely local to Lynx.
\par Some documents are designated\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 index documents\plain \f1\fs18 \~by virtue of an ISINDEX element in their HEAD section. These documents can be used to retrieve additional information based on searches using words or phrases submitted to an index server. The Lynx statusline will indicate that you are viewing such a document, and if so, the '\plain \f1\i\fs18 s\plain \f1\fs18 ' key will invoke a statusline prompt to enter a query string. The prompt can be specified via a PROMPT attribute in the ISINDEX element. Otherwise, Lynx will use an internally configured prompt. The address for submitting the search can be specified via an HREF or ACTION attribute. Otherwise, Lynx will use the current document's URL and append your query string as a\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 ?searchpart\plain \f1\fs18 \~(see\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 Supported URLs\plain \f1\fs18 ).
\par All search words or strings which you have entered during a Lynx session are saved in a circular buffer, and can be retrieved for re-use by pressing the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 up-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~or\plain \f1\i\fs18 down-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~keys at the prompt for a search word or string. Also, you can use the '\plain \f1\i\fs18 n\plain \f1\fs18 'ext command to repeat a search with the last-entered search word or phrase, starting from the current position in the document. The word or phrase matches will be highlighted throughout the document, but such highlighting will not persist for new documents, or if the current document is reloaded. The search cycles to the top of the document if the word or phrase is not located below your current position.
\par Although\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 HTML Forms\plain \f1\fs18 \~have largely replaced index documents for searches via http servers, they are still useful for performing searches directly via WAIS or Gopher servers in conjunction with the internal gateways for such servers. For example, an HTML index document can act as a\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 cover page\plain \f1\fs18 \~describing a WAIS database and how to formulate query strings for searching it, and include an element such as:
\par \plain \f1\i\fs18 <ISINDEX PROMPT="Enter WAIS query:"\'0a 
\par                HREF="wais://net.bio.net/biologists-addresses">
\par \plain \f1\fs18 for submitting a search of the Biologist's Addresses database directly to the net.bio.net WAIS server. [\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]
