\par {\*\bkmkstart Mail}{\*\bkmkend Mail}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Comments and mailto: links
\par \plain \f1\fs18 At any time while viewing documents within Lynx, you may use the '\plain \f1\i\fs18 c\plain \f1\fs18 ' command to send a mail message to the owner of the current document if the author of the document has specified ownership. (Note to authors: if you want to assign the ownership to your document, you need to add into HEAD section a LINK element with appropriate value for REV attribute. Two values are recognized:\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 owner\plain \f1\fs18 \~and\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 made\plain \f1\fs18 \~(these are case insensitive). For example,<HEAD>\'0a 
\par     \uc2\u8230 \'a1\'ad\'0a \uc1
\par     <LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:user@somedomain.com">\'0a 
\par     \uc2\u8230 \'a1\'ad\'0a<\uc1
\par </HEAD>\'0a
\par You may also add a TITLE attribute with, for example, the name of your page) If no ownership is specified then comments are disabled. Certain links called\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 mailto:\plain \f1\fs18 links will also allow you to send mail to other people. Using the mail features within Lynx is straightforward.
\par Once you have decided to send a comment or have selected a\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 mailto:\plain \f1\fs18 \~link a new screen will appear showing you to whom you are sending the message. Lynx will ask for your name, your e-mail address, and the subject of the message. If you have filled in the "personal mail address" field in the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Options Menu\plain \f1\fs18 , your e-mail address will be filled in automatically. After entering the above information, if you have an editor defined in the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Options Menu\plain \f1\fs18 \~and you are not an anonymous user then your specified editor will be spawned for you so that you can enter your message. If you do not have an editor defined or you are an anonymous user, a simple line mode input scheme will allow you to enter your message.
\par To finish sending the message, exit your spawned editor or, if you are using the simple line mode input scheme, type a '\plain \f1\i\fs18 .\plain \f1\fs18 ' (period) on a line by itself. You will be asked a final time whether to send the message. If you press '\plain \f1\i\fs18 y\plain \f1\fs18 ', you will be prompted whether to append your signature file if one was defined in\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 lynx.cfg\plain \f1\fs18 \~and is accessible, and then the message will be sent, whereas if you press '\plain \f1\i\fs18 n\plain \f1\fs18 ' the message will be deleted. Entering Control-G in response to any prompts also will cancel the mailing.[\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]
\par {\*\bkmkstart News}{\*\bkmkend News}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 USENET News posting
\par \plain \f1\fs18 While reading\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 news\plain \f1\fs18 \~articles with Lynx you should see a link that says\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Reply to: user@host\plain \f1\fs18 \~and, if the nntp server from which you received the article supports posting from your site, a link that says\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Followup to: newsgroup(s)\plain \f1\fs18 Reply to user@hostuser@host will correspond to the mail address of the person who posted the news article. Selecting the link will allow you to send a message to the person who wrote the message you are currently viewing. You will be given the option of including the original message in your reply.Followup to newsgroup(s)Selecting this link will allow you to post back to the newsgroup that you are currently reading and any newsgroups to which the message was cross-posted. You will be given the option of including the original message in your reply. Once you have typed in your message, you will be asked for confirmation of whether to proceed with the posting, and whether to append your signature file if one was defined in\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 lynx.cfg\plain \f1\fs18 \~and is accessible. See\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 Supported URLs\plain \f1\fs18 \~for more information about the URL schemes for posting or sending followups (replies) to nntp servers with Lynx. [\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]See also\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 RFC 977\plain \f1\fs18 .
\par {\*\bkmkstart Bookmarks}{\*\bkmkend Bookmarks}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Lynx bookmarks
\par \plain \f1\fs18 Bookmarks are entries in your\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 bookmark file\plain \f1\fs18 , which record the URL of a document you may want to return to easily, with a name of your choice to identify the document. To use bookmarks you must first have specified a name for your bookmark file in\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 lynx.cfg\plain \f1\fs18 \~or via the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Options Menu\plain \f1\fs18 .
\par To save a bookmark to the document you wish to place in the bookmark file press the '\plain \f1\i\fs18 a\plain \f1\fs18 ' key and you will be asked:
\par \pard\li720\fi-360\jclisttab\tx720\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\listtext\pard\plain\f4\fs24 \tab}\ls5\ilvl0 \plain \f1\fs18 Save D)ocument or L)ink to bookmark file or C)ancel? (d,l,c):
\par \plain\pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f1\fs18 Answer '\plain \f1\i\fs18 d\plain \f1\fs18 ' to save a link to the document you are currently viewing or '\plain \f1\i\fs18 l\plain \f1\fs18 ' to save the link that is currently selected on the page. Selecting '\plain \f1\i\fs18 c\plain \f1\fs18 ' will cancel without saving anything to your bookmark file.
\par A bookmark file will be created in conjunction with acting on the '\plain \f1\i\fs18 a\plain \f1\fs18 'dd command if it does not already exist. Otherwise, the link will be added to the bottom of the pre-existing bookmark file. You must have created a bookmark file via the '\plain \f1\i\fs18 a\plain \f1\fs18 'dd command before you can view it.
\par Use the '\plain \f1\i\fs18 v\plain \f1\fs18 ' command to view the list of bookmarks you have saved. While viewing the bookmark list you may select a bookmark as you would any other link.
\par You can remove a link from the bookmark list by pressing the '\plain \f1\i\fs18 r\plain \f1\fs18 ' key when positioned on that link. You also can use a standard text editor (e.g., via the '\plain \f1\i\fs18 e\plain \f1\fs18 'dit command while viewing a bookmark file, if an external editor has been defined via the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Options menu\plain \f1\fs18 ) to delete or re-order links in the bookmark file, or to modify a link name by editing the content of the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 A\plain \f1\fs18 nchor element for the link, but you should not change the format within the line for the link, consisting of an\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 LI\plain \f1\fs18 \~element followed by the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 A\plain \f1\fs18 nchor element, nor cause the line to become wrapped to a second line. You similarly can change the link destination by editing the double-quoted value for the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 HREF\plain \f1\fs18 \~attribute in the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 A\plain \f1\fs18 nchor start tag, but you should not otherwise change the spacing within the start tag, nor add other attributes. You can add a new link while editing by copying an existing line for a link, to ensure the proper format, and then modifying its\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 HREF\plain \f1\fs18 \~value and\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 A\plain \f1\fs18 nchor content, but you should not add any other HTML markup to the bookmark file. If the format and spacing (other than the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 A\plain \f1\fs18 nchor content or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 HREF\plain \f1\fs18 \~value) within lines is changed or other HTML markup is added, the '\plain \f1\i\fs18 a\plain \f1\fs18 'dd and '\plain \f1\i\fs18 r\plain \f1\fs18 'emove commands may not work properly.
\par When multi-bookmarks (see\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 Options Menu\plain \f1\fs18 ) is OFF, you will always view or add links to the default bookmark file. When it is STANDARD, a menu of up to 26 bookmark files will be invoked, and you select the bookmark file by entering its letter token. When it is ADVANCED, you will be prompted for the letter token, but can enter '\plain \f1\i\fs18 =\plain \f1\fs18 ' to invoke the STANDARD selection menu, or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 RETURN\plain \f1\fs18 \~for the default bookmark file. [\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]
\par {\*\bkmkstart Jumps}{\*\bkmkend Jumps}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Jump Command
\par \plain \f1\fs18 Similar to the bookmarks file is the jumps file: for an example, look in the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 samples\plain \f1\fs18 \~subdirectory in the distribution package. To use the jumps command, create a\plain \f1\i\fs18 jumps file\plain \f1\fs18 \~with the same format as the sample file, but containing your own URLs & short-cut names. Once you have done that, typing '\plain \f1\i\fs18 j\plain \f1\fs18 ' prompts you to enter a short-cut name, which will take you straight to the URL associated with the short-cut in the jumps file, much like using '\plain \f1\i\fs18 g\plain \f1\fs18 '. If you want to check which short-cuts are available, type '\plain \f1\i\fs18 ?\plain \f1\fs18 ' at the jump prompt for the full list.
\par All jump short-cuts you have entered are saved in a circular buffer in the same way as with '\plain \f1\i\fs18 g\plain \f1\fs18 ' and '\plain \f1\i\fs18 /\plain \f1\fs18 ' (search):
\par previous entries can be retrieved with\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 up-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 down-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 .
\par The jumps feature is especially useful for system administrators who have unsophisticated users to care for, but ordinary Lynx users who have a number of URLs they regularly visit while browsing may find using the jumps command speeds their movements.
\par For more advice how to set up the jumps command on your system and how to define short-cut names, read\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 lynx.cfg\plain \f1\fs18 \~. [\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]
\par {\*\bkmkstart DirEd}{\*\bkmkend DirEd}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Directory Editing
\par \plain \f1\fs18 Lynx offers extended DIRED support on Unix (on VMS the more powerful CSwing program is recommended for character cell terminals, and can be offered via Lynx as a jump shortcut or execution link). When a local directory is accessed using a URL of the form\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 file://localhost/path/\plain \f1\fs18 , a new set of commands is available. With DIRED support you can create, edit, delete, copy, and move files on your local system. The commands available in DIRED mode areC)reateType '\plain \f1\i\fs18 c\plain \f1\fs18 ' to create a new file. New file will be empty.D)ownloadType '\plain \f1\i\fs18 d\plain \f1\fs18 ' to download using one of the pre-defined options.E)ditType '\plain \f1\i\fs18 e\plain \f1\fs18 ' to spawn the editor defined in\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Options Menu\plain \f1\fs18 \~and load a selected file for editing.F)ull MenuType '\plain \f1\i\fs18 f\plain \f1\fs18 ' to show full menu of options available for selection. Menu may vary according to type of file selected and compression facilities available.M)odifyType '\plain \f1\i\fs18 m\plain \f1\fs18 ' to modify the name or location of file. Then type '\plain \f1\i\fs18 n\plain \f1\fs18 ' to rename the file or '\plain \f1\i\fs18 l\plain \f1\fs18 ' to move the file to a different location.R)emoveType '\plain \f1\i\fs18 r\plain \f1\fs18 ' to remove the selected file or directory.T)agType '\plain \f1\i\fs18 t\plain \f1\fs18 ' to tag highlighted file. Further operations will be performed on tagged files instead of highlighted ones.U)ploadType '\plain \f1\i\fs18 u\plain \f1\fs18 ' to upload a file to the present directory. An uploading method must have been pre-defined in\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 lynx.cfg\plain \f1\fs18 \~.[\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]
\par {\*\bkmkstart ColorMouse}{\*\bkmkend ColorMouse}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Using Color & the Mouse
\par \plain \f1\fs18 A limited range of colors & mouse commands are available, if the user chooses: see\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 lynx.cfg\plain \f1\fs18 \~for details. [\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]
\par {\*\bkmkstart MiscKeys}{\*\bkmkend MiscKeys}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Scrolling and Other useful commands
\par \plain \f1\fs18 A summary of all the keystroke commands and their key bindings can be invoked via the KEYMAP command, normally mapped to '\plain \f1\i\fs18 k\plain \f1\fs18 ' and '\plain \f1\i\fs18 K\plain \f1\fs18 '. The following describes some of the most commonly used commands.\plain \f1\i\fs18 ^AControl-A\plain \f1\fs18 \~jumps you to the beginning of the current document. It is a synonym for the Keypad\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Home\plain \f1\fs18 \~key, and can be used also when\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Links are numbered\plain \f1\fs18 \~mode is on. The\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Find\plain \f1\fs18 \~Function key also is a synonym, and ideally the latter has been mapped to the Function key labeled\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Home\plain \f1\fs18 \~if you are using an IBM Enhanced Keyboard.\plain \f1\i\fs18 ^EControl-E\plain \f1\fs18 \~jumps you to the end of the current document. It is a synonym for the Keypad\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 End\plain \f1\fs18 \~key, and can be used also when\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Links are numbered\plain \f1\fs18 \~mode is on. The\plain \f1\i\fs18 Select\plain \f1\fs18 \~Function key also is a synonym, and ideally the latter has been mapped to the Function key labeled\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 End\plain \f1\fs18 \~if you are using an IBM Enhanced Keyboard.\plain \f1\i\fs18 ^BControl-B\plain \f1\fs18 \~normally jumps you to the previous page of the current document, and thus is a synonym for the Keypad and Function\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Page-Up\plain \f1\fs18 \~keys. However,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Control-B\plain \f1\fs18 acts as\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 right-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~when emacs-like key movement is enabled (see\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 Lynx Options Menu\plain \f1\fs18 ).\plain \f1\i\fs18 ^FControl-F\plain \f1\fs18 \~normally jumps you to the next page of the current document, and thus is a synonym for the Keypad and Function\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Page-Down\plain \f1\fs18 \~keys. However,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Control-F\plain \f1\fs18 becomes\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 right-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~when emacs-like key movement is enabled.\plain \f1\i\fs18 ^NControl-N\plain \f1\fs18 \~normally jumps you forward two lines in the current document. The\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Remove\plain \f1\fs18 \~Function key (labeled\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Delete\plain \f1\fs18 \~on IBM Enhanced keyboards, and distinct from their\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Backspace\plain \f1\fs18 \~key) is a synonym.\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Control-N\plain \f1\fs18 \~becomes\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 down-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~when emacs-like key movement is enabled.\plain \f1\i\fs18 ^PControl-P\plain \f1\fs18 \~normally jumps you back two lines in the current document. The\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Insert\plain \f1\fs18 \~Function key is a synonym.\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Control-P\plain \f1\fs18 \~becomes\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 up-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~when emacs-like key movement is enabled.\plain \f1\i\fs18 )\plain \f1\fs18 The\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 )\plain \f1\fs18 \~command jumps you forward half a page in the current document.\plain \f1\i\fs18 (\plain \f1\fs18 The\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 (\plain \f1\fs18 \~command jumps you back half a page in the current document.\plain \f1\i\fs18 #\plain \f1\fs18 The '\plain \f1\i\fs18 #\plain \f1\fs18 ' command jumps you to the pseudo Toolbar or Banner if present in the current document. Use\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 left-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~to return from there to your previous position in the document.\plain \f1\i\fs18 !\plain \f1\fs18 When '\plain \f1\i\fs18 !\plain \f1\fs18 ' is pressed your default shell will be spawned. When you quit or exit the shell you will return to Lynx (usually\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 exit\plain \f1\fs18 \~under Unix and\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 logout\plain \f1\fs18 \~under VMS). This command is usually disabled for anonymous users. On VMS, '\plain \f1\i\fs18 $\plain \f1\fs18 ' normally is a synonym. On Win32, this has no effect [???].\plain \f1\i\fs18 g\plain \f1\fs18 The '\plain \f1\i\fs18 g\plain \f1\fs18 ' command allows any URL to be viewed. Pressing the '\plain \f1\i\fs18 g\plain \f1\fs18 ' command will bring up a prompt asking for a URL. Type in the URL that you wish to view. All previously entered goto URLs are saved in a circular buffer, and can be accessed at the prompt by pressing the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 up-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 down-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~keys.\plain \f1\i\fs18 G\plain \f1\fs18 The '\plain \f1\i\fs18 G\plain \f1\fs18 ' command allows you to edit the URL of the current document and then use that as a goto URL. Pressing the '\plain \f1\i\fs18 G\plain \f1\fs18 ' command will bring up a prompt asking you to edit the current document's URL. If you do not modify it, or completely delete it, or enter Control-G, the command will be cancelled. If the current document has POST content associated with it, an Alert will be issued. If you do edit that URL, and it does not simply involve a fragment change (for seeking a position in the current document), the modified URL will be submitted with method GET and no POST content. If a modification of the current document's URL results in a submission, that modified URL will be entered into the circular buffer for goto URLs, and can be accessed for further modification via the '\plain \f1\i\fs18 g\plain \f1\fs18 ' command.\plain \f1\i\fs18 E\plain \f1\fs18 The '\plain \f1\i\fs18 E\plain \f1\fs18 ' command allows you to edit the URL (or ACTION) of the current link and then use that as a goto URL. Pressing the '\plain \f1\i\fs18 E\plain \f1\fs18 ' command will bring up a prompt asking you to edit the current link's URL. If you do not modify it, or completely delete it, or enter Control-G, the command will be cancelled. Otherwise, the request for the 'E'dited URL will be sent with method GET, and will be entered into the circular buffer for goto URLs so that it can be accessed for further modification via the '\plain \f1\i\fs18 g\plain \f1\fs18 ' command. Note that lower case 'e' invokes the external editor for the current document.\plain \f1\i\fs18 =\plain \f1\fs18 The '\plain \f1\i\fs18 =\plain \f1\fs18 ' command shows information about the current document and the currently selected link if there is one. The number of lines in the file, URL, title, owner, and type are shown.\plain \f1\i\fs18 ^TControl-T\plain \f1\fs18 \~toggles Lynx trace mode on and off. This is useful for diagnosing bad html. If you get a\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Bad HTML\plain \f1\fs18 \~statusline message when loading a document, enter\plain \f1\i\fs18 Control-T\plain \f1\fs18 \~and then\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Control-R\plain \f1\fs18 \~to reload the document in trace mode. You may then examine the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Lynx Trace Log\plain \f1\fs18 \~file with the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 ;\plain \f1\fs18 \~command if enabled (see below), watch out especially for lines marked with a number of asterisks '*****'. You also can submit the document for validation via links in the online help menu. If you are able to diagnose the problem, send a message about it to the document's author.\plain \f1\i\fs18 ;\plain \f1\fs18 The\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 ;\plain \f1\fs18 \~command shows the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Lynx Trace Log\plain \f1\fs18 \~(\plain \f1\i\fs18 Lynx.trace\plain \f1\fs18 \~in the home directory) if one has been started for the current session. If a log has not been started, any trace messages will be sent to the screen (and will disturb the normal display) unless the system supports piping and that was used to redirect stderr messages to a file. The log is started when Lynx trace mode is turned on via the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 -trace\plain \f1\fs18 \~command line switch, or via the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Control-T\plain \f1\fs18 \~toggle, if Lynx has been compiled to log the trace and other stderr messages by default. If not, ability to create a log can be toggled on with the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 -tlog\plain \f1\fs18 \~switch. Note that this ability is probably disabled in anonymous or validation accounts.{\*\bkmkstart asterisk_key}{\*\bkmkend asterisk_key}\plain \f1\i\fs18 *\plain \f1\fs18 The '\plain \f1\i\fs18 *\plain \f1\fs18 ' command toggles image_links mode on and off. When on, links will be created for all images, including inline images. If you have an image viewer mapped to the image's MIME type, you can activate such links to view an inline image. You should normally have this mode toggled off.\plain \f1\i\fs18 @\plain \f1\fs18 The '\plain \f1\i\fs18 @\plain \f1\fs18 ' command toggles raw 8-bit or CJK mode on and off. When on, the charset is assumed to match the selected character set and 8-bit characters are not reverse translated with respect to the ISO-8859-1 conversion tables.{\*\bkmkstart lbracket_key}{\*\bkmkend lbracket_key}\plain \f1\i\fs18 [\plain \f1\fs18 The '\plain \f1\i\fs18 [\plain \f1\fs18 ' command toggles pseudo_inlines mode on and off. When on, inline images which have no ALT string specified will have an\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 [INLINE]\plain \f1\fs18 \~pseudo-ALT string inserted in the Lynx display. When off, they will be treated as having ALT="" (i.e., they'll be ignored). If image_links mode is toggled on, the pseudo-ALT strings will be restored, to serve as links to the inline images' sources.\plain \f1\i\fs18 ]\plain \f1\fs18 The '\plain \f1\i\fs18 ]\plain \f1\fs18 ' command is used to send HEAD requests for the current document or link. It applies only to documents or links (or form submit buttons) of http servers. A statusline message will notify you if the context for this command was inappropriate. The HEAD requests always are sent to the http server, i.e., Lynx does not retrieve any previous server replies from its cache. Note that for form submissions, http servers vary in whether they'll treat HEAD requests as valid and return the CGI script's headers, or treat it as invalid and return an error message.\plain \f1\i\fs18 ^KControl-K\plain \f1\fs18 \~invokes the\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 Cookie Jar Page\plain \f1\fs18 \~if it contains cookies.\plain \f1\i\fs18 ^XControl-X\plain \f1\fs18 \~invokes the\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 Cache Jar Page\plain \f1\fs18 \~if it contains cached documents.\plain \f1\i\fs18 z\plain \f1\fs18 Lynx supports completely interruptible I/O processes. Press the '\plain \f1\i\fs18 z\plain \f1\fs18 ' key at any time during a connect or transfer process and the process will be halted. If any data was transferred before the interrupt, it will be displayed.\plain \f1\i\fs18 numbers\plain \f1\fs18 Lynx offers other, advanced navigation features when numbers are used to invoke the\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 Follow Link (or goto link or page) number:\plain \f1\fs18 \~or\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 Select Pop-up Option Number:\plain \f1\fs18 prompts. [\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]
\par {\*\bkmkstart Forms}{\*\bkmkend Forms}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Lynx and HTML Forms
\par \plain \f1\fs18 This section describes the Lynx Forms Interface. HTML gives document providers the ability to create on-line forms which may be filled out when the document is viewed. When a form is submitted the information on the form can be used to search a database or complete a survey.
\par An HTML Form provides for the use of buttons to perform an action (such as\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 submit\plain \f1\fs18 ), checkboxes, radio buttons or popups to select options from a list, and fields for entering text.
\par Buttons:Buttons are displayed in the same way that Lynx displays links in a document. To "push" the button press the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 right-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Return\plain \f1\fs18 \~key. If it is a form submission button, you also can use the NOCACHE ('\plain \f1\i\fs18 x\plain \f1\fs18 ') or DOWNLOAD ('\plain \f1\i\fs18 d\plain \f1\fs18 ') keystroke commands to "push" the button (see below).Checkboxes and Radio buttonsCheckboxes are displayed as square brackets:\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 [ ]\plain \f1\fs18 \~and radio buttons are displayed as parenthesis:\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 ( )\plain \f1\fs18 . When a box is checked or a button selected, an\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 x\plain \f1\fs18 \~appears in the brackets:\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 [x]\plain \f1\fs18 \~or an asterisk appears within the parenthesis:\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 (*)\plain \f1\fs18 . To check a box or select a radio button press the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 right-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Return\plain \f1\fs18 \~key.Selection FieldsSelection fields are displayed as brackets with the default option displayed between them:\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 [default__]\plain \f1\fs18 . To select an option press the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 right-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Return\plain \f1\fs18 \~key. A box with a border of asterisks (or line-drawing characters) will pop up with the list of possible options listed within the box. Use the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 up-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 down-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 ,\plain \f1\i\fs18 page-up\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 page-down\plain \f1\fs18 , and other navigation keys to move the cursor among options, and the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 right-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Return\plain \f1\fs18 \~key to select an option. You also can use the '\plain \f1\i\fs18 /\plain \f1\fs18 ' and '\plain \f1\i\fs18 n\plain \f1\fs18 'ext\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 searching\plain \f1\fs18 \~commands for navigating to options which contain particular strings.\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 NOTE\plain \f1\fs18 \~that the popup menu feature can be disabled via compilation and/or configuration options, or via the\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 Options Menu\plain \f1\fs18 , in which case the selection field options will be converted to a list of radio buttons. The default setting for use of popups or radio button lists can be toggled via the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 -popup\plain \f1\fs18 \~command line switch.Text Entry FieldsText entry (INPUT) fields are displayed as a row of underscores the length of the entry field:\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 _______\plain \f1\fs18 . You may enter text directly by typing at the keyboard. Use the\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 Line Editor\plain \f1\fs18 \~keys to correct errors. If you try to input more text than the field can hold, the line editor will not accept the additional characters. If you fill a text field the cursor will not move off the field but remain at the last field position. Use the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 up-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 , and\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 down-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 TAB\plain \f1\fs18 \~or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Return\plain \f1\fs18 \~keys to move up, or down from the text entry field. NOTE, however, that\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Return\plain \f1\fs18 \~also will\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 submit\plain \f1\fs18 \~the form if the text entry field is the only non-hidden field in the form. If{\*\bkmkstart tna}{\*\bkmkend tna}"Textfields Need Activation"\~mode is turned on (with the\~-tna\~command-line option or in\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 lynx.cfg\plain \f1\fs18 ), then text entry fields do not become active immediately upon being selected, as normally. Keystrokes have their normal command meaning unless the Line Editor gets activated with\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Return\plain \f1\fs18 \~or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Right Arrow\plain \f1\fs18 . This mode can be used to avoid "getting stuck" in input fields, especially by users who rarely fill out forms.
\par {\*\bkmkstart CtrlVNote}{\*\bkmkend CtrlVNote}NOTE:\~If you have a text input field selected you will not have access to most of the Lynx keystroke commands, because they are interpreted by the\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 Line Editor\plain \f1\fs18 \~as either text entries or editing commands. Select a button or box when you want to use Lynx keystrokes; or prefix your keystroke with\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 ^V\plain \f1\fs18 \~to temporarily escape from line editing.
\par Some flavors of UNIX, shells & terminal settings require that you enter\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 ^V^Ve\plain \f1\fs18 \~in order to start the external editor, as they also use\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 ^V\plain \f1\fs18 \~as default command-line quote key (called `lnext' in stty man pages and `stty -a' output); to avoid this, you can put `stty lnext undef' in your .cshrc file (or .profile or .bashrc, depending on what shell you use), or invoke Lynx with a wrapper script, e.g.
\par \~\~#!/bin/sh
\par \~\~stty lnext undef
\par \~\~$HOME/bin/lynx "$@"
\par \~\~stty lnext ^V
\par \~\~exit
\par NB when NOT in the Line Editor,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 ^V\plain \f1\fs18 \~is by default bound to the command to switch between SortaSGML and TagSoup HTML parsing (i.e., SWITCH_DTD). To avoid confusion, either of these separate functions could be changed (mapped away) with a KEYMAP directive in\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 lynx.cfg\plain \f1\fs18 . For example,
\par \~\~KEYMAP:^V:DO_NOTHING
\par \~\~KEYMAP:#:SWITCH_DTD
\par would map SWITCH_DTD away from\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 ^V\plain \f1\fs18 \~to\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 #\plain \f1\fs18 , while leaving its default Line Editor function as a command escape in place. On the other hand,
\par \~\~KEYMAP:^V::NOP:1
\par \~\~KEYMAP:^_::LKCMD:1
\par would move\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 ^V\plain \f1\fs18 's Line Editor binding as command escape to\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 ^_\plain \f1\fs18 \~for the first Line Edit style, letting\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 ^V\plain \f1\fs18 \~still act as SWITCH_DTD outside of text input fields.
\par TEXTAREA FieldsTEXTAREA fields are for most purposes handled as if they were a series of text entry (INPUT) fields for which successive lines imply a newline at the end of the preceding line. You enter text on each line to construct the overall message. Any blank lines at the bottom of the TEXTAREA field will be eliminated from the submission. The\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 up-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 , and\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 down-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Return\plain \f1\fs18 \~keys move you to the preceding, or next line of the overall message, as for INPUT fields. The\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 TAB\plain \f1\fs18 \~key will move you down beyond the bottom of the TEXTAREA field, and\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Back Tab\plain \f1\fs18 \~(if available, e.g., as Shift-Tab, and correctly mapped in the terminal description) will move backward to a link or field before the TEXTAREA.Editing TEXTAREA Fields and Special TEXTAREA FunctionsTEXTAREA fields can be edited using an external editor. The statusline should tell you when this is possible and what key to use, it might for example say\plain \f1\b\fs18           (Textarea) Enter text. \plain \f1\fs18 [ ..... ]\plain \f1\b\fs18  (^Xe for editor).\plain \f1\fs18 An external editor has to be defined, for example in the\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 Options Menu\plain \f1\fs18 , before you can start using this function.
\par A key to invoke external TEXTAREA editing is normally provided by the\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 Line-Editor Key\plain \f1\fs18 \~Bindings. A KEYMAP directive in\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 lynx.cfg\plain \f1\fs18 \~can also be used to make a different key invoke external editing; it will then normally be necessary to prefix that key with\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 ^V\plain \f1\fs18 \~to "escape" from line-editing. Two variants exist,
\par \~\~KEYMAP:e:EDITTEXTAREA
\par or
\par \~\~KEYMAP:e:DWIMEDIT
\par (the first is only functional for TEXTAREA editing, while the second allows to use the same key for normal\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 file editing\plain \f1\fs18 \~\plain \f1\i\fs18 as long as both functions don't conflict\plain \f1\fs18 ).
\par Please see the\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 note above\plain \f1\fs18 \~for details about\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 ^V\plain \f1\fs18 \~behavior.
\par You can also use two other special TEXTAREA functions. Again, these are already bound to key sequences in the\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 Line-Editor Bindings\plain \f1\fs18 , by default\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 ^Xg\plain \f1\fs18 \~and\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 ^Xi\plain \f1\fs18 . You can use different keys by adding KEYMAP bindings to your\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 lynx.cfg\plain \f1\fs18 \~file, e.g.
\par \~\~KEYMAP:$:GROWTEXTAREA
\par \~\~KEYMAP:#:INSERTFILE
\par With these bindings, (in a TEXTAREA only)\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 ^V$\plain \f1\fs18 \~would add 5 lines to the TEXTAREA and\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 ^V#\plain \f1\fs18 \~would prompt for the name of an existing file to be inserted into the TEXTAREA (above the cursorline). An automatic variation of GROWTEXTAREA is normally compiled in, so that hitting\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Enter\plain \f1\fs18 \~with the cursor on the last line adds a new line to the TEXTAREA, with the cursor on it.
\par If you have some single keys (or control keys) to spare that you do not need for their normal purposes, you can dedicate those keys to invoke the special functions (without requiring a prefix key). For example, to use the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 ^E\plain \f1\fs18 \~key for the DWIMEDIT action, and the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Insert\plain \f1\fs18 \~key for the INSERTFILE action, use
\par \~\~KEYMAP:^E:DWIMEDIT:PASS
\par \~\~KEYMAP:0x10C:INSERTFILE:PASS
\par (see lynx.cfg for other keystroke codes to use).
\par Note that the default bindings that use\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 ^X\plain \f1\fs18 \~as a prefix key\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 may\plain \f1\fs18 \~also work by substituting the\~Escape\~key for ^X. If your keyboard has a modifier (Meta) key that gets transmitted as an ESC prefix, for example\~Alt, you can then even use\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Alt-e\plain \f1\fs18 \~instead of\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 ^Xe\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Alt-g\plain \f1\fs18 \~instead of\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 ^Xg\plain \f1\fs18 , and so on. But this does not work reliably everywhere (it depends on the way Lynx is compiled, including which libraries are used, and behavior of the connection and terminal type).
\par In general, you can move around the form using the standard Lynx navigation keys. The\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 up-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~and\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 down-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~keys, respectively, select the previous or next field, box, or button. The\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 TAB\plain \f1\fs18 \~key selects the next field, box, or button.
\par To\~{\*\bkmkstart submit}{\*\bkmkend submit}\plain \f1\i\fs18 submit\plain \f1\fs18 \~the form press\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 right-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Return\plain \f1\fs18 \~when positioned on the form's submit button. If you've submitted the form previously during the Lynx session, have not changed any of the form content, and the METHOD was\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 GET\plain \f1\fs18 , Lynx will retrieve from its cache what was returned from the previous submission. If you wish to resubmit that form to the server with the same content as previously, use the NOCACHE command ('\plain \f1\i\fs18 x\plain \f1\fs18 ') when positioned on the submit button. The\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 right-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~and\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Return\plain \f1\fs18 \~keys also will invoke a no-cache resubmission if the reply from a form submission included a META element with a no-cache Pragma or Cache-Control directive:
\par \plain \f1\i\fs18 <META HTTP-EQUIV="Pragma" CONTENT="no-cache">
\par       <META HTTP-EQUIV="Cache-Control" CONTENT="no-cache">
\par \plain \f1\fs18 or the server sent a "Pragma" or "Cache-Control" MIME header with a no-cache directive.
\par You also can use the DOWNLOAD ('\plain \f1\i\fs18 d\plain \f1\fs18 ') keystroke command when positioned on a form submit button if you wish to download the server's reply to the submission instead of having Lynx render and display it.
\par Forms which have\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 POST\plain \f1\fs18 \~as the METHOD, or a\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 mailto:\plain \f1\fs18 \~URL as the ACTION, are always resubmitted, even if the content has not changed, when you activate the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 submit\plain \f1\fs18 \~button. Lynx normally will not resubmit a form which has\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 POST\plain \f1\fs18 \~as the METHOD if the document returned by the form has links which you activated, and then you go back via the PREV_DOC (\plain \f1\i\fs18 left-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 ) command or via the\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 History Page\plain \f1\fs18 . Lynx can be compiled so that it resubmits the form in those cases as well, and the default can be changed via\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 lynx.cfg\plain \f1\fs18 , and toggled via the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 -resubmit_posts\plain \f1\fs18 \~command line switch.
\par If the form has one\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 text entry\plain \f1\fs18 \~field and no other fields except, possibly, hidden INPUT fields not included in the display, then that field also serves as a\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 submit\plain \f1\fs18 button, and pressing\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 right-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Return\plain \f1\fs18 \~on that field will invoke submission of the form. Be sure to use\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 up-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 down-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 TAB\plain \f1\fs18 \~to move off the text entry field, in such cases, if it is not your intention to submit the form (or to retrieve what was returned from an earlier submission if the content was not changed and the METHOD was\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 GET\plain \f1\fs18 ).
\par Forms can have multiple\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 submit\plain \f1\fs18 \~buttons, if they have been assigned NAMEs in the markup. In such cases, information about which one of the buttons was used to submit the form is included in the form content.
\par Inlined images can be used as submit buttons in forms. If such buttons are assigned NAMEs in the markup, for graphic clients they can also serve as\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 image maps\plain \f1\fs18 , and the x,y coordinates of the graphic client's cursor position in the image when it was\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 clicked\plain \f1\fs18 \~are included in the form content. Since Lynx cannot inline the image, and the user could not have moved a cursor from the origin for the image, if no alternatives are made available in the markup Lynx sends a 0,0 coordinate pair in the form content. Document authors who use images as submit buttons, but have at least some concern for text clients and sight-challenged Webizens, should include VALUEs for the buttons in such markup. Lynx will then display the string assigned to the VALUE, as it would for a normal submit button. Some document authors incorrectly use an ALT instead of VALUE attribute for this purpose. Lynx "cooperates" by treating ALT as a synonym for VALUE when present in an INPUT tag with TYPE="image". If neither a VALUE nor an ALT attribute is present, Lynx displays "[IMAGE]-Submit" as the string for such buttons. If clickable images is set, the "[IMAGE]" portion of the string is a link for the image, and the "Submit" portion is the button for submitting the form. Otherwise, the entire string is treated as a submit button. If a VALUE or ALT attribute is present and clickable images is set, Lynx prepends "[IMAGE]" as a link for the image, followed by '-' and then the attribute's value as the displayed string for the submit button. Note that earlier versions of Lynx would send a name=value pair instead of a 0,0 coordinate pair if a TYPE="image" submit button was NAME-ed, had a VALUE attribute in the INPUT tag, and was used to submit the form. The script which analyzes the form content thus could be made aware whether the submission was by a user with a graphic client and had image loading turned on, or by a user who did not see the image nor make a conscious choice within it. However, requests that this be included in HTML specifications consistently have fallen on deaf ears, and thus Lynx now "fakes" a 0,0 coordinate pair whether or not a VALUE or ALT attribute is present in the INPUT tag. Ideally, the script which analyzes the submitted content will treat the 0,0 coordinate pair as an indicator that the user did not see the image and make a conscious choice within it.
\par Forms can have\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 hidden\plain \f1\fs18 \~INPUT fields, which are not displayed, but have NAMEs and VALUEs included in the content. These often are used to keep track of information across a series of related form submissions, but have the potential for including information about the user that might be considered to represent an invasion of privacy. NOTE, in this regard, that Lynx has implemented the\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 HTML 3.0\plain \f1\fs18 \~\plain \f1\i\fs18 DISABLED\plain \f1\fs18 \~attribute for\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 all\plain \f1\fs18 \~of its form fields. These can be used to keep track of information across submissions, and to cast it unmodifiable in the current form, but keep the user aware that it will be included in the submission.
\par Forms most commonly are submitted to http servers with the content encoded as\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 ENCTYPE="application/x-www-form-urlencoded"\plain \f1\fs18 \~for analysis by a script, and Lynx treats that as the default if no ENCTYPE is specified in the FORM start tag. However, you can specify a\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 mailto\plain \f1\fs18 \~URL as the form's ACTION to have the form content sent, instead, to an email address. In such cases, you may wish to specify\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 ENCTYPE="text/plain"\plain \f1\fs18 \~in the form markup, so that the content will not be encoded, but remain readable as plain text.
\par Lynx also supports\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 ENCTYPE="application/sgml-form-urlencoded"\plain \f1\fs18 \~for which all reserved characters in the content will be hex escaped, as with\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 application/x-www-form-urlencoded\plain \f1\fs18 , but semicolons ('\plain \f1\i\fs18 ;\plain \f1\fs18 ') instead of ampersands ('\plain \f1\i\fs18 &\plain \f1\fs18 ') will be used as the separator for name=value pairs in the form content. The use of semicolons is preferred for forms with the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 GET\plain \f1\fs18 \~METHOD, because the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 GET\plain \f1\fs18 \~METHOD causes the encoded form content to be appended as a\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 ?searchpart\plain \f1\fs18 \~for the form's ACTION, and if such URLs are used in\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 text/html\plain \f1\fs18 \~documents or bookmark files without conversion of the ampersands to SGML character references (\plain \f1\i\fs18 &amp;\plain \f1\fs18 \~or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 &#38;\plain \f1\fs18 ), their being followed by form field NAMEs which might correspond to SGML entities could lead to corruption of the intended URL.
\par NOTE, in this regard, that Lynx converts ampersands to\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 &amp;\plain \f1\fs18 \~when creating bookmarks, and thus the bookmark links will not be vulnerable to such corruptions. Also NOTE that Lynx allows you to save links in your bookmark file for documents returned by forms with the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 GET\plain \f1\fs18 \~METHOD, and which thus have the content appended as a\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 ?searchpart\plain \f1\fs18 , but not if the METHOD was\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 POST\plain \f1\fs18 , because the content would be lost and the link thus would be invalid.
\par Lynx supports\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 ENCTYPE="multipart/form-data"\plain \f1\fs18 \~for sending form content with name=value pairs encoded as multipart sections with individual MIME headers and boundaries. However, Lynx does not yet support INPUTs with\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 TYPE="file"\plain \f1\fs18 \~or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 TYPE="range"\plain \f1\fs18 \~and will set the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 DISABLED\plain \f1\fs18 \~attribute for all of the form's fields if any INPUTs with either of those two TYPEs are present, so that the form can't be submitted. Otherwise, Lynx will submit the form with the multipart ENCTYPE.
\par A\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Content-Disposition:\~file;\~filename=name.suffix\plain \f1\fs18 \~header can be used by CGI scripts to set the suggested filename offered by Lynx for '\plain \f1\i\fs18 d\plain \f1\fs18 'ownload and '\plain \f1\i\fs18 p\plain \f1\fs18 'rint menu options to save or mail the body returned by the script following submission of a FORM. Otherwise, Lynx uses the last symbolic element in the path for the FORM's ACTION, which is normally the script, itself, or a PATH_INFO field, and thus might be misleading. This also can be done via a META element in any document:
\par \plain \f1\i\fs18 <META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Disposition"\'0a 
\par             CONTENT="file;\~filename=name.suffix">
\par \plain \f1\fs18 [\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]
\par {\*\bkmkstart Images}{\*\bkmkend Images}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Lynx and HTML Images
\par \plain \f1\fs18 As a text browser, Lynx does not display images as such -- you need to define a viewer in\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 lynx.cfg\plain \f1\fs18 : see there -- , but users can choose a number of ways of showing their presence.
\par There are 3 choices in\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 lynx.cfg\plain \f1\fs18 , with 2 corresponding keys:
\par MAKE_LINKS_FOR_ALL_IMAGES        *  IMAGE_TOGGLE\'0a 
\par      MAKE_PSEUDO_ALTS_FOR_INLINES     [  INLINE_TOGGLE\'0a 
\par      VERBOSE_IMAGES                   no corresponding key\'0a
\par 
\par You can also use the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Options Menu\plain \f1\fs18 , as outlined below:
\par key  lynx.cfg       FM KM .lynxrc    variable in source\'0a\'0a
\par 
\par        *  MAKE_LINKS_     Y  N       N    clickable_images\'0a 
\par        [  MAKE_PSEUDO_    Y  N       N    pseudo_inline_alts\'0a 
\par           VERBOSE_        Y  Y       Y    verbose_img\'0a\'0a
\par \'0aF
\par FM = Form-based Menu ; KM = Key-based Menu ;\'0ai
\par in  .lynxrc ,  VERBOSE_IMAGES  is called `verbose_images':\'0at
\par the other two cannot be saved between sessions.\'0a
\par 
\par In the Form-based Menu, the 3-way `Show images' selection combines the effects of the `*' & `[' keys, as follows:
\par Ignore      clickable_images = FALSE, pseudo_inline_alts = FALSE\'0a 
\par      As labels   clickable_images = FALSE, pseudo_inline_alts = TRUE\'0a 
\par      As links    clickable_images = TRUE,  pseudo_inline_alts = unchanged\'0a
\par 
\par {\*\bkmkstart Tables}{\*\bkmkend Tables}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Lynx and HTML Tables
\par \plain \f1\fs18 HTML includes markup for creating\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 tables\plain \f1\fs18 \~structured as arrays of cells aligned by columns and rows on the displayed page.
\par Lynx recognizes the TABLE element and all of its associated elements as described in\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 RFC 1942\plain \f1\fs18 \~and will process any ID attributes in the start tags for handling as NAME-ed anchors, but does not create actual\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 tables\plain \f1\fs18 . Instead, it treats the TR start tag as a collapsible BR (line break), and inserts a collapsible space before the content of each TH and TD start tag. This generally makes all of the content of the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 table\plain \f1\fs18 \~readable, preserves most of the intra-cell organization, and makes all of the links in the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 table\plain \f1\fs18 \~accessible, but any information critically dependent on the column and row alignments intended for the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 table\plain \f1\fs18 \~will be missed.
\par If inherently tabular data must be presented with Lynx, one can use PRE formatted content, or, if the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 table\plain \f1\fs18 \~includes markup not allowed for PRE content, construct the\plain \f1\i\fs18 table\plain \f1\fs18 \~using\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 HTML Tabs\plain \f1\fs18 . An example\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 table\plain \f1\fs18 \~using\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 TAB\plain \f1\fs18 \~elements is included in the test subdirectory of the Lynx distribution.
\par Starting with version 2.8.3, Lynx renders some tables in tabular form. This tabular representation for\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 simple\plain \f1\fs18 \~tables (TRST) does not attempt to implement full support for any table model. Limitations are:
\par \pard\li720\fi-360\jclisttab\tx720\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\listtext\pard\plain\f3\fs24\lang1024 \uc2\u183 \'a1\'a4\uc1\tab}\ls6\ilvl0 \plain \f1\fs18 All data constituting a table row generally has to fit within the display width without inserting line breaks.
\par \plain{\listtext\pard\plain\f3\fs24\lang1024 \uc2\u183 \'a1\'a4\uc1\tab}\ls6\ilvl0 \plain \f1\fs18 Cell contents have to be simple. In general, only inline markup is acceptable, no\~<P>,\~<BR>\~etc. (although\~<BR>\~may be ignored at the beginning of the first cell or at the end of the last cell of a row).
\par \plain{\listtext\pard\plain\f3\fs24\lang1024 \uc2\u183 \'a1\'a4\uc1\tab}\ls6\ilvl0 \plain \f1\fs18 When tables are nested, only the innermost level is a candidate for tabular representation.
\par \plain{\listtext\pard\plain\f3\fs24\lang1024 \uc2\u183 \'a1\'a4\uc1\tab}\ls6\ilvl0 \plain \f1\fs18 Most attributes are ignored, including borders,\~WIDTH, vertical alignment.
\par \plain\pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f1\fs18 Horizontal alignments (LEFT,\~CENTER,\~RIGHT),\~COLSPAN, and\~ROWSPAN\~are interpreted according to HTML 4.01. (ROWSPAN\~can only reserve empty space in subsequent rows, because of the limitations above.) When TRST fails because a table is not "simple" enough, the representation falls back to the minimal handling described earlier. Many (but, unfortunately, by no means all) tables that represent inherently tabular material will thus be shown with correct tabular formatting. Where table markup is used only for layout purposes (containing whole blocks of text and list within table cells) and not essential for understanding the textual contents, it remains basically ignored. Some more information on details is available in the file\~README.TRST\~of the source distribution.
\par For tabular display of more complex tables, Lynx users can make use of external scripts or programs. The normal Lynx distribution currently does not provide such scripts, but they can be written locally or downloaded from several sources. It is suggested to use one of Lynx's facilities for invoking external programs (seeDOWNLOADER,\~PRINTER,\~EXTERNAL,\~TRUSTED_LYNXCGI\~in\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 lynx.cfg\plain \f1\fs18 \~and\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 lynxcgi:\plain \f1\fs18 \~in\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Supported URLs\plain \f1\fs18 \~for information on various ways for setting this up). [\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]
\par {\*\bkmkstart Tabs}{\*\bkmkend Tabs}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Lynx and HTML Tabs
\par \plain \f1\fs18 Lynx implements the\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 HTML 3.0\plain \f1\fs18 \~TAB element only when LEFT alignment is in effect. If the alignment is CENTER or RIGHT (JUSTIFY is not yet implemented in Lynx, and is treated as a synonym for LEFT), or if the TAB element indicates a position to the left of the current position on the screen, it is treated as a collapsible space. For purposes of implementing TAB, Lynx treats\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 en\plain \f1\fs18 \~units as half a character cell width when specified by the INDENT attribute, and rounds up for odd values (e.g., a value of either 5 or 6 will be treated as three spaces, each the width of a character cell). See the example\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 table\plain \f1\fs18 \~using TAB elements in the test subdirectory of the Lynx distribution as a model for using this functionality.
\par Note that this\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Users Guide\plain \f1\fs18 \~and the\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 Supported URLs\plain \f1\fs18 \~page include TAB markup in a manner which\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 degrades gracefully\plain \f1\fs18 \~for WWW browsers which do not support it. Toggle to display of\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 source\plain \f1\fs18 \~and\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 search\plain \f1\fs18 \~for\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 <tab\plain \f1\fs18 \~to examine the use of TAB markup in these documents. [\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]
\par {\*\bkmkstart Frames}{\*\bkmkend Frames}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Lynx and HTML Frames
\par \plain \f1\fs18 Some implementations of HTML include markup, primarily designed for graphic clients, that is intended to create an array of simultaneously displayed, independently scrolling windows. Such windows have been termed\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 frames\plain \f1\fs18 .
\par Lynx recognizes the Netscape and Microsoft Explorer FRAME, FRAMESET, and NOFRAMES elements, but is not capable of windowing to create the intended positioning of\plain \f1\i\fs18 frames\plain \f1\fs18 . Instead, Lynx creates labeled links to the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 frame\plain \f1\fs18 \~sources, typically positioned in the upper left corner of the display, and renders the NOFRAMES section. If the document provider has disregard for text clients and sight-challenged Webizens, and thus does not include substantive content in the NOFRAMES section or a link in it to a document suitable for text clients, you can usually guess from the labeling of the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 frame\plain \f1\fs18 \~links which one has the substantive material (if there is any), or you can try each of those links to see if anything worthwhile is returned. [\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]
\par Some sites -- in ignorance of Lynx capabilities -- may tell you (for example) "to view this page you need Netscape Navigator". You can simply ignore such warnings and access the frames via the Lynx-generated links as above.
\par {\*\bkmkstart Banners}{\*\bkmkend Banners}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Lynx and HTML Banners
\par \plain \f1\fs18 Some implementations of HTML markup include provisions for creating a non-scrolling window to be positioned at the top of each page, containing links with brief, descriptive link names, analogous to a Windows toolbar. Such windows have been termed\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 banners\plain \f1\fs18 .
\par Lynx recognizes and processes all of the\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 HTML 3.0\plain \f1\fs18 \~REL attribute tokens in LINK elements for creating a\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 banner\plain \f1\fs18 , and a number of others which have subsequently been proposed. These\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 banner\plain \f1\fs18 \~tokens are\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Home\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Contents\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Index\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Glossary\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Copyright\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Up\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Next\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Previous\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Prev\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Help\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Search\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Top\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Origin\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Navigator\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Child\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Disclaimer\plain \f1\fs18 ,\plain \f1\i\fs18 Sibling\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Parent\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Author\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Editor\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Publisher\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Trademark\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Meta\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 URC\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Hotlist\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Begin\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 First\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 End\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Last\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Pointer\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Translation\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Definition\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Chapter\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Section\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Subsection\plain \f1\fs18 ,\plain \f1\i\fs18 Alternate\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Documentation\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Biblioentry\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Bibliography\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Start\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Appendix\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Bookmark\plain \f1\fs18 \~and\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Banner\plain \f1\fs18 . Any LINK elements with those tokens as the REL attribute value, and an HREF attribute value in the LINK, will invoke creation of a\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 banner\plain \f1\fs18 \~at the top of the first page, with the element's HREF as the link, and the token as the default link name. If a TITLE attribute is included in the LINK, it's value will be used as the link name instead of the default.\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Bookmark\plain \f1\fs18 \~and\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Banner\plain \f1\fs18 \~are intended to be accompanied by a TITLE attribute, which in effect makes the namespace for REL\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 banner\plain \f1\fs18 \~tokens infinite.
\par If the special token\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Help\plain \f1\fs18 \~is used as the REL value and no HREF is included in the LINK, Lynx will use it own\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 HELPFILE\plain \f1\fs18 \~URL for that link. For the special token\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Home\plain \f1\fs18 without an HREF, Lynx will use the default\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 STARTFILE\plain \f1\fs18 \~(i.e., derived from the configuration files or the WWW_HOME environment variable,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 not\plain \f1\fs18 \~the command line\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 startfile\plain \f1\fs18 if one was used). However, if a\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 -homepage=URL\plain \f1\fs18 \~was specified on the command line, it's URL will be used as the HREF. For the special token\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Index\plain \f1\fs18 \~without an HREF, Lynx will use the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 DEFAULT_INDEX_FILE\plain \f1\fs18 \~derived from the configuration files, or if an\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 -index=URL\plain \f1\fs18 \~was specified on the command line, it's URL will be used as the HREF.
\par Lynx does not waste screen real estate maintaining the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 banner\plain \f1\fs18 \~at the top of every page, but the Lynx TOOLBAR keystroke command ('\plain \f1\i\fs18 #\plain \f1\fs18 ') will, any time it is pressed, position you on the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 banner\plain \f1\fs18 \~so that any of its links can be activated, and pressing the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 left-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~when in the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 banner\plain \f1\fs18 \~will return you to where you were in the current document. The toolbar is indicated by a '\plain \f1\i\fs18 #\plain \f1\fs18 " preceding its first link when present on the screen, that is, when the first page of the document is being displayed. The availability of a toolbar is indicated by a '\plain \f1\i\fs18 #\plain \f1\fs18 ' at the top, left-hand corner of the screen when the second or subsequent pages of the document are being displayed.
\par Lynx also recognizes the\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 HTML 3.0\plain \f1\fs18 \~BANNER container element, and will create a\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 banner\plain \f1\fs18 \~based on its content if one has not already been created based on LINK elements. Lynx treats the Microsoft MARQUEE element as a synonym for BANNER (i.e., presenting it's markup as a static\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 banner\plain \f1\fs18 , without any horizontal scrolling of its content). Lynx does not prefix the BANNER or MARQUEE content with a '\plain \f1\i\fs18 #\plain \f1\fs18 ' because the content need not be only a series of links with brief, descriptive links names, but does add a '\plain \f1\i\fs18 #\plain \f1\fs18 ' at the top, left-hand corner of the screen when the content is not being displayed, to indicate it's accessibility via the TOOLBAR keystroke command. [\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]
\par {\*\bkmkstart Footnotes}{\*\bkmkend Footnotes}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Lynx and HTML Footnotes
\par \plain \f1\fs18 Lynx implements the\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 HTML 3.0\plain \f1\fs18 \~FN element similarly to a named\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 A\plain \f1\fs18 nchor within the current document, and assumes that the footnotes will be positioned at the bottom of the document. However, in contrast to named\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 A\plain \f1\fs18 nchors, the FN container element is treated as a block (i.e., as if a new paragraph were indicated whether or not that is indicated in its content) with greater than normal left and right margins, and the block will begin with a\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 FOOTNOTE:\plain \f1\fs18 \~label. For example, if the document contains:        See the \plain \f1\i\fs18 <A HREF="#fn1">\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 footnote\plain \f1\i\fs18 </A>\plain \f1\fs18 .\'0a
\par activating that link will take you to the labeled rendering of:\plain \f1\i\fs18         <FN ID="fn1">\plain \f1\fs18 <p>{\*\bkmkstart an1}{\*\bkmkend an1}Lynx does not use popups for FN blocks.</p>\plain \f1\i\fs18 </FN>
\par \plain \f1\fs18 
\par i.e., position it at the top of the page. Then, upon reading the footnote, you can return to your previous position in the document by pressing the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 left-arrow\plain \f1\fs18 \~key. The content of an FN element can be any HTML markup that is valid in the BODY of the document. [\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]
\par {\*\bkmkstart Notes}{\*\bkmkend Notes}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Lynx and HTML Notes
\par \plain \f1\fs18 Lynx implements the\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 HTML 3.0\plain \f1\fs18 \~NOTE element (\plain \f1\i\fs18 Admonishment\plain \f1\fs18 ) as a labeled block, i.e., as if a new paragraph were indicated whether or not paragraphing markup is included in its content, with greater than normal left and right margins, and with the type of note indicated by an emphasized label based on the value of its CLASS or ROLE attribute. If no CLASS or ROLE attribute is included, the default label\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 NOTE:\plain \f1\fs18 \~will be used. Lynx recognizes the values\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 caution\plain \f1\fs18 \~and\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 warning\plain \f1\fs18 , for which, respectively, the labels\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 CAUTION:\plain \f1\fs18 \~or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 WARNING:\plain \f1\fs18 \~will be used. The NOTE element can have an ID attribute, which will be treated as a named\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 A\plain \f1\fs18 nchor, as for\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 HTML Footnotes\plain \f1\fs18 , but the NOTE block need not be placed at the bottom of the document. The content of a NOTE block can be any HTML markup that is valid in the BODY of the document. This is an example:
\par \plain \f1\i\fs18 <NOTE CLASS="warning" ID="too-bad">\'0a 
\par         <p>The W3C vendors did not retain NOTE in the HTML 3.2 draft.</p>\'0a 
\par       </NOTE>
\par \plain \f1\fs18 It will\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 degrade gracefully\plain \f1\fs18 \~for WWW browsers which do not support NOTE, except for recognition of the ID attribute as a named\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 A\plain \f1\fs18 nchor. [\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]
\par {\*\bkmkstart Lists}{\*\bkmkend Lists}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Lynx and HTML Lists
\par \plain \f1\fs18 Lynx implements the\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 HTML 3.0\plain \f1\fs18 \~list elements UL (\plain \f1\i\fs18 Unordered List\plain \f1\fs18 ), OL (\plain \f1\i\fs18 Ordered List\plain \f1\fs18 ), and DL (\plain \f1\i\fs18 Definition List\plain \f1\fs18 ), and their associated attributes, and elements (LH, LI, DT, and DD) for the most part as described in that specification. The lists can be nested, yielding progressively greater indentation, up to six levels. The\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 HTML 2.0\plain \f1\fs18 MENU and DIR elements\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 both\plain \f1\fs18 \~are treated as synonyms for UL with the PLAIN attribute (no\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 bullets\plain \f1\fs18 , see below). Note, thus, that neither DIR nor MENU yields a series of columns with 24-character spacing. A single nesting index is maintained, so that different types of List elements can be used for different levels within the nest. Also, the\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 HTML 3.0\plain \f1\fs18 \~FIG, CAPTION and CREDIT elements are treated as valid within list blocks. They will be rendered with indentation appropriate for the current nesting depth, and the CAPTION or CREDIT elements will have a\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 CAPTION:\plain \f1\fs18 \~or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 CREDIT:\plain \f1\fs18 \~label beginning the first line of their content. The content of any APPLET or OBJECT elements in the lists also will be indented appropriately for the current nesting depth, but those will not invoke line breaks unless indicated by their content, and it should not include markup which is inappropriate within the list.
\par Lynx also supports the TYPE attribute for OL elements, which can have values of\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 1\plain \f1\fs18 \~for Arabic numbers,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 I\plain \f1\fs18 \~or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 i\plain \f1\fs18 \~for uppercase or lowercase Roman numerals, or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 A\plain \f1\fs18 \~or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 a\plain \f1\fs18 \~for uppercase or lowercase letters, that increment for successive LI elements in the list block. The CONTINUE attribute can be used to continue the ordering from the preceding list block when the nesting depth is changed.
\par Lynx treats the OL attributes START and SEQNUM as synonyms for specifying the ordering value for the first LI element in the block. The values should be specified as Arabic numbers, but will be displayed as Arabic, Roman, or alphabetical depending on the TYPE for the block. The values can range from\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 -29997\plain \f1\fs18 \~to the system's maximum positive integer for Arabic numbers. For Roman numerals, they can range from\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 1\plain \f1\fs18 \~(\plain \f1\i\fs18 I\plain \f1\fs18 \~or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 i\plain \f1\fs18 ) to\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 3000\plain \f1\fs18 \~(\plain \f1\i\fs18 MMM\plain \f1\fs18 \~or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 mmm.\plain \f1\fs18 ). For alphabetical orders, the values can range from\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 1\plain \f1\fs18 \~(\plain \f1\i\fs18 A\plain \f1\fs18 or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 a\plain \f1\fs18 ) to\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 18278\plain \f1\fs18 \~(\plain \f1\i\fs18 ZZZ\plain \f1\fs18 \~or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 zzz\plain \f1\fs18 ). If the CONTINUE attribute is used, you do not need to specify a START or SEQNUM attribute to extend the ordering from a previous block, and you can include a TYPE attribute to change among Arabic, Roman, or alphabetical ordering styles, or their casing, without disrupting the sequence. If you do not include a START, SEQNUM or CONTINUE attribute, the first LI element of each OL block will default to\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 1\plain \f1\fs18 , and if you do not include a TYPE attribute, Lynx defaults to Arabic numbers.
\par For UL blocks without the PLAIN attribute, Lynx uses\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 *\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 +\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 o\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 #\plain \f1\fs18 ,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 @\plain \f1\fs18 \~and\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 -\plain \f1\fs18 \~as\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 bullets\plain \f1\fs18 \~to indicate, progressively, the depth within the six nesting levels.
\par Lynx treats UL, OL, DIR, and MENU blocks as having the COMPACT attribute by default, i.e., single spaces between LH and LI elements within those blocks. For DL blocks, double spacing will be used to separate the DT and DD elements unless the COMPACT attribute has been specified. [\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]
\par {\*\bkmkstart Quotes}{\*\bkmkend Quotes}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Lynx and HTML Quotes
\par \plain \f1\fs18 The\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 HTML 3.0\plain \f1\fs18 \~and later specifications provide for two classes of quotation in HTML documents. Block quotes, designated by the BLOCKQUOTE element (or it's abbreviated synonym BQ in HTML 3.0), have implied paragraph breaks preceding and following the start and end tags for the block. Character level quotes, designated by the Q element, in contrast are simply directives in the markup to insert an appropriate quotation mark.
\par Lynx renders block quotes with a greater than normal left and right indentation. Lynx does not support italics, and normally substitutes underlining, but does not underline block quotes so as not to obscure any explicit emphasis elements within the quotation. The BLOCKQUOTE or BQ block can include a CREDIT container element, whose content will be rendered as an implied new paragraph with a\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 CREDIT:\plain \f1\fs18 \~label at the beginning of its first line.
\par Lynx respects nested Q start and end tags, and will use ASCII double-quotes (\plain \f1\i\fs18 "\plain \f1\fs18 ) versus grave accent (\plain \f1\i\fs18 `\plain \f1\fs18 ) and apostrophe (\plain \f1\i\fs18 '\plain \f1\fs18 ), respectively, for even versus odd depths in the nest.
\par Any ID attributes in BLOCKQUOTE, BQ or Q elements can be the target of a hyperlink in the form URL#id. It is treated just like the NAME in\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 A\plain \f1\fs18 nchors. [\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]
\par {\*\bkmkstart Eightbit}{\*\bkmkend Eightbit}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Lynx and HTML Internationalization: 8bit, UNICODE, etc.
\par \plain \f1\fs18 Lynx has superior support for HTML 4.0/I18N internationalization issues. However, to see the characters other than 7bit properly you\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 should\plain \f1\fs18 \~set your\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 display character set\plain \f1\fs18 \~from Option Menu and save its value, this is a Frequently Asked Question. Fine-turning is also available from\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 lynx.cfg\plain \f1\fs18 \~[\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]
\par {\*\bkmkstart USEMAP}{\*\bkmkend USEMAP}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Lynx and Client-Side-Image-Maps
\par \plain \f1\fs18 HTML includes markup, designed primarily for graphic clients, that treats inlined images as maps, such that areas of the image within which a mouse cursor was positioned when the mouse was\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 clicked\plain \f1\fs18 \~can correspond to URLs which should be retrieved. The original implementations were based on the client sending an http server the x,y coordinates associated with the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 click\plain \f1\fs18 , for handling by a script invoked by the server, and have been termed\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 server-side-image-maps\plain \f1\fs18 . Lynx has no rational way of coping with such a procedure, and thus simply sends a 0,0 coordinate pair, which some server scripts treat as an instruction to return a document suitable for a text client.
\par Newer HTML markup provides bases for the client to determine the URLs associated with areas in the image map, and/or for a text client to process alternative markup and allow the user to make choices based on textual information. These have been termed\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 client-side-image-maps\plain \f1\fs18 .
\par Lynx recognizes and processes the MAP container element and its AREA elements, and will create a menu of links for the HREF of each AREA when the link created for the IMG element with a USEMAP attribute is activated. The menu uses the ALT attributes of the AREA elements as the link names, or, if the document's author has disregard for text clients and sight-challenged Webizens, and thus did not include ALT attributes, Lynx uses the resolved URLs pointed to by the HREF attributes as the link names. Lynx uses the TITLE attribute of the IMG element, or the TITLE attribute of the MAP, if either was present in the markup, as the title and main header of the menu. Otherwise, it uses the ALT attribute of the IMG element. If neither TITLE nor ALT attributes were present in the markup, Lynx creates and uses a\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 [USEMAP]\plain \f1\fs18 pseudo-ALT. The MAPs need not be in the same document as the IMG elements. If not in the same document, Lynx will fetch the document which contains the referenced MAP, and locate it based on its NAME or ID attribute. All MAPs encountered in documents during a Lynx session are cached, so that they need not be retrieved repeatedly when referenced in different documents.
\par If the IMG element also indicates a\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 server-side-image-map\plain \f1\fs18 \~via an ISMAP attribute, Lynx normally will create a link for that as well, using an\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 [ISMAP]\plain \f1\fs18 \~pseudo-ALT (followed by a hyphen to indicate its association with the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 client-side-image-map\plain \f1\fs18 ) rather than ignoring it, and will submit a 0,0 coordinate pair if that link is activated. Although, the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 client-side-image-map\plain \f1\fs18 \~may be more useful for a client such as Lynx, because all of the URLs associated with the image map can be accessed, and their nature indicated via ALT attributes, Lynx-friendly sites can map 0,0 such that the server returns a for-text-client document homologous to the content of FIG elements (see below). Inclusion of such a link for submissions to the server can be disabled by default via the configuration file (\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 lynx.cfg\plain \f1\fs18 ), and the default can be toggled via the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 -ismap\plain \f1\fs18 \~command line switch.
\par Lynx also recognizes the\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 HTML 3.0\plain \f1\fs18 \~FIG and OVERLAY elements, and will handle them as intended for text clients. These are the ideal way to handle\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 client-side-image-maps\plain \f1\fs18 , because the FIG content provides complete alternative markup, rather than relying on the client to construct a relatively meager list of links with link names based on ALT strings.
\par The presently experimental OBJECT element encompasses much of the functionality of the FIG element for\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 client-side-image-maps\plain \f1\fs18 . Lynx will render and display the content of OBJECT elements which have the SHAPES attribute equivalently to its handling of FIG. Lynx also handles OBJECT elements with the USEMAP and/or ISMAP attributes equivalently to its handling of IMG elements with\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 client-side-image-maps\plain \f1\fs18 \~and/or\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 server-side-image-maps\plain \f1\fs18 . [\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]
\par {\*\bkmkstart Refresh}{\*\bkmkend Refresh}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Lynx and Client-Side-Pull
\par \plain \f1\fs18 HTML includes provision for passing instructions to clients via directives in META elements, and one such instruction, via the token\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Refresh\plain \f1\fs18 , should invoke reloading of the document, fetched from a server with the same URL or a new URL, at a specified number of seconds following receipt of the current document. This procedure has been termed\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 client-side-pull\plain \f1\fs18 . An example of such an element is:\plain \f1\i\fs18       <META HTTP-EQUIV="Refresh" CONTENT="3; URL=http://host/path">
\par \plain \f1\fs18 which instructs a client to fetch the indicated URL in 3 seconds after receiving the current document. If the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 URL=\plain \f1\fs18 \~field is omitted, the URL defaults to that of the current document. A\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 no-cache\plain \f1\fs18 \~directive is implied when the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Refresh\plain \f1\fs18 \~if for the same URL.
\par Lynx recognizes and processes\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Refresh\plain \f1\fs18 \~directives in META elements, but puts up a labeled link, typically in the upper left corner of the display, indicating the number of seconds intended before a refresh, and the URL for the refresh, instead of making the request automatically after the indicated number of seconds. This allows people using a braille interface any amount of time to examine the current document before activating the link for the next URL. In general, if the number of seconds indicated is short, the timing is not critical and you can activate the link whenever you like. If it is long (e.g., 60 seconds), a server process may be generating new documents or images at that interval, and you would be wasting bandwidth by activating the link at a shorter interval. [\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]
\par {\*\bkmkstart Cookies}{\*\bkmkend Cookies}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Lynx State Management\plain \f1\b\fs18 \~\plain \f1\fs18 (Me want\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 cookie\plain \f1\fs18 !)
\par HTTP provides a means to carry state information across successive connections between a browser and an http server. Normally, http servers respond to each browser request without relating that request to previous or subsequent requests. Though the inclusion of INPUT fields with TYPE="hidden" can be used as a sort of state management by\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 HTML Forms\plain \f1\fs18 , a more general approach involves exchanges of MIME headers between the server and browser. When replying to a request, the server can send a\plain \f1\i\fs18 Set-Cookie\plain \f1\fs18 \~MIME header which contains information (\plain \f1\i\fs18 cookies\plain \f1\fs18 ) relevant to the browser's request, and in subsequent requests the browser can send a\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Cookie\plain \f1\fs18 \~MIME header with information derived from previously received cookies.
\par State Management via cookie exchanges originally was implemented by Netscape, and such cookies are now designated as\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Version 0\plain \f1\fs18 . A more elaborate format for cookies, designated as\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Version 1\plain \f1\fs18 , is being standardized by the IETF (Internet Engineering Task Force). Lynx supports both\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Version 0\plain \f1\fs18 \~and\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Version 1\plain \f1\fs18 \~cookie exchanges. This support can be disabled by default via the SET_COOKIES symbol in the compilation (\plain \f1\i\fs18 userdefs.h\plain \f1\fs18 ) and/or run time (\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 lynx.cfg\plain \f1\fs18 ) configuration files, and that default setting can be toggled via the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 -cookies\plain \f1\fs18 \~command line switch. The SET_COOKIES symbol can be further modified by the ACCEPT_ALL_COOKIES mode. If ACCEPT_ALL_COOKIES is set TRUE, and SET_COOKIES is TRUE, Lynx will accept all cookies. Additionally, the cookies that are automatically accepted or rejected by Lynx can be further modified with the COOKIE_ACCEPT_DOMAINS and COOKIE_REJECT_DOMAINS options in your .lynxrc file, each of which is a comma-separated list of domains to perform the desired action. The domain listed in these options must be identical to the domain the cookie comes from, there is no wildcard matching. If a domain is specific in both COOKIE_ACCEPT_DOMAINS and COOKIE_REJECT_DOMAINS, rejection will take precedence.
\par When cookie support is enabled,\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Set-Cookie\plain \f1\fs18 \~MIME headers received from an http server invoke confirmation prompts with possible replies of '\plain \f1\i\fs18 Y\plain \f1\fs18 'es or '\plain \f1\i\fs18 N\plain \f1\fs18 'o for acceptance of the cookie, '\plain \f1\i\fs18 A\plain \f1\fs18 'lways to accept the cookie and to allow all subsequent cookies from that\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 domain\plain \f1\fs18 \~(server's Fully Qualified Domain Name, or site-identifying portion of the FQDN) without further confirmation prompts, or ne'\plain \f1\i\fs18 V\plain \f1\fs18 'er to never allow cookies from that\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 domain\plain \f1\fs18 \~to be accepted (silently ignore its\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Set-Cookie\plain \f1\fs18 \~MIME headers). All unexpired cookies are held in a hypothetical\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Cookie Jar\plain \f1\fs18 \~which can be examined via the COOKIE_JAR keystroke command, normally mapped to\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Ctrl-K\plain \f1\fs18 , for invoking the\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 Cookie Jar Page\plain \f1\fs18 . If Lynx has been compiled with the --enable-persistent-cookies flag, then unexpired cookies will be stored between sessions in the filename set with the COOKIE_FILE option in your .lynxrc.
\par A common use of cookies by http servers is simply to track the documents visited by individual users. Though this can be useful to the site's WebMaster for evaluating and improving the organization of links in the various documents of the site, if the user has configured Lynx to include a\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 From\plain \f1\fs18 \~MIME header with the user's email address in http requests, or has passed personal information to the server via a form submission, the tracking might be used to draw inferences, possibly incorrect, about that user, and may be considered by some as an invasion of privacy.
\par An example of worthwhile State Management via cookies is the setting of personal preferences, typically via a form submission to the site, which will then apply to all documents visited at that site.
\par If you accept cookies when accessing a site, but are given no indication about how they will be used in subsequent requests to that site, nor can infer how they will be used, you can\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Gobble\plain \f1\fs18 \~(delete) the cookies and/or change the 'allow' setting for its\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 domain\plain \f1\fs18 \~via the\~\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 Cookie Jar Page\plain \f1\fs18 . [\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]
\par {\*\bkmkstart Cache}{\*\bkmkend Cache}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Cached Documents
\par \plain \f1\fs18 A list of documents which are in lynx's internal cache is accessible through hypothetical\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Cache Jar\plain \f1\fs18 \~which can be examined via the CACHE_JAR keystroke command, normally mapped to\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Ctrl-X\plain \f1\fs18 .
\par Entries in the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Cache Jar\plain \f1\fs18 \~are ordered from oldest (at the top) to newest. The user can easily access any document which is in the cache, especially those which may be soon removed due to configurable limits on the maximum number of cached documents, as well as the maxmimum amount of memory used by the cache.
\par The structure of\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Cache Jar\plain \f1\fs18 \~is simple:
\par \pard\li720\fi-360\jclisttab\tx720\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\listtext\pard\plain\f3\fs24\lang1024 \uc2\u183 \'a1\'a4\uc1\tab}\ls7\ilvl0 \plain \f1\fs18 Each entry starts with its ordinal number (within the session), recently added documents in cache have a smaller number than documents which are added before, and are positioned at the end of\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 Cache Jar
\par \plain{\listtext\pard\plain\f3\fs24\lang1024 \uc2\u183 \'a1\'a4\uc1\tab}\ls7\ilvl0 \plain \f1\fs18 Following its ordinal number is the document title, which is also a link. On activating this link, the user is prompted if they want to delete the document from\plain \f1\i\fs18 Cache Jar\plain \f1\fs18 . The document's address (also a link) follows the title. It is distinguished by a\~URL:\~label preceding the link. Activating this link, lynx displays the corresponding cached document.
\par \plain{\listtext\pard\plain\f3\fs24\lang1024 \uc2\u183 \'a1\'a4\uc1\tab}\ls7\ilvl0 \plain \f1\fs18 Below each cached document URL lynx shows the document properties which include:
\par \plain\pard\li1080\fi-360\jclisttab\tx1080\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\listtext\pard\plain\f5\fs24 o\tab}\ls7\ilvl1 \plain \f1\fs18 Lines,
\par \plain{\listtext\pard\plain\f5\fs24 o\tab}\ls7\ilvl1 \plain \f1\fs18 Size,
