\par {\*\bkmkstart Sessions}{\*\bkmkend Sessions}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 Sessions
\par \plain \f1\fs18 Lynx's current state (all information about the user's current activity with lynx) is called a session. Sessions are useful in particular if you are in the middle of exploring something on the web and you were forced to stop abruptly, losing any trace of your current work.
\par A session can be automatically restored as lynx starts after a clean exit. The session data is saved if lynx is invoked with the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 -session=FILENAME\plain \f1\fs18 \~switch. The\plain \f1\i\fs18 FILENAME\plain \f1\fs18 \~is the name of the file where the session will be stored.
\par There are also switches for only restoring:\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 -sessionin=FILENAME\plain \f1\fs18 \~and for only saving:\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 -sessionout=FILENAME\plain \f1\fs18 \~sesions:
\par If you do not want to specify these options at each lynx startup, there is an option in\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 lynx.cfg\plain \f1\fs18 \~to enable automatic saving/restoring of session. To keep lynx startup/exit reasonable fast there is also an option in\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 lynx.cfg\plain \f1\fs18 \~specifying how much information about the current lynx session will be stored in file.
\par The syntax of the session file is simple. You can use a text editor to modify, add new entries, or remove URLs you no longer want. [\plain \f1\ul\fs18\cf1 ToC\plain \f1\fs18 ]
\par {\*\bkmkstart Invoking}{\*\bkmkend Invoking}\plain \f1\b\i\fs18 The Lynx command line
\par \plain \f1\fs18 A summary of the Lynx command line options (switches) is returned to stdout if Lynx is invoked with the\~\plain \f1\i\fs18 -help\plain \f1\fs18 \~switch. A description of the options also should be available via the system man (Unix) pages or help (VMS) libraries. On Win32, typing lynx -help in a DOS window should display similarly. The basic syntax of the Lynx command line can be represented as one of the following:Commandlynx [options]lynx [options] startfilewherestartfileis the file or URL that Lynx will load at start-up.
\par \pard\li720\fi-360\jclisttab\tx720\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 {\listtext\pard\plain\f3\fs24\lang1024 \uc2\u183 \'a1\'a4\uc1\tab}\ls8\ilvl0 \plain \f1\fs18 If startfile is not specified, Lynx will use a default starting file and base directory determined during installation.
\par \plain{\listtext\pard\plain\f3\fs24\lang1024 \uc2\u183 \'a1\'a4\uc1\tab}\ls8\ilvl0 \plain \f1\fs18 If a specified file is local (i.e., not a URL) Lynx displays that file and uses the directory in which that file resides as the base directory.
\par \plain{\listtext\pard\plain\f3\fs24\lang1024 \uc2\u183 \'a1\'a4\uc1\tab}\ls8\ilvl0 \plain \f1\fs18 If a URL is specified, the file will be retrieved, and only the server base directory will be relevant to further accesses.
\par \plain{\listtext\pard\plain\f3\fs24\lang1024 \uc2\u183 \'a1\'a4\uc1\tab}\ls8\ilvl0 \plain \f1\fs18 If more than one local file or remote URL is listed on the command line, Lynx will open only the last interactively. All of the names (local files and remote URLs) are added to the G)oto history.
\par \plain\pard\fi0\li0\ql\ri0\sb0\sa0\itap0 \plain \f1\fs18 optionsLynx uses only long option names. Option names can begin with double dash as well, underscores and dashes can be intermixed in option names (in the reference below options are with one dash before them and with underscores).
\par Lynx provides many command-line options. Some options require a value (string, number or keyword). These are noted in the reference below. The other options set boolean values in the program. There are three types of boolean options: set, unset and toggle. If no option value is given, these have the obvious meaning: set (to true), unset (to false), or toggle (between true/false). For any of these, an explicit value can be given in different forms to allow for operating system constraints, e.g.,
\par 
\par -center:off\'0a 
\par               -center=off\'0a 
\par               -center-Lynx recognizes "1", "+", "on" and "true" for true values, and "0", "-", "off" and "false" for false values. Other option-values are ignored.
\par The default boolean, number and string option values that are compiled into lynx are displayed in the help-message provided by lynx -help. Some of those may differ according to how lynx was built; see the help message itself for these values. The -help option is processed before any option, including those that control reading from the lynx.cfg file. Therefore runtime configuration values are not reflected in the help-message.
